# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: acetyl-coa
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:acetyl-coa/1-3-bisphosphoglycerate] 1,3-Bisphosphoglycerate is the conjugate base of 1,3-bisphosphoglyceric acid.
[src:acetyl-coa/1-3-bisphosphoglycerate] It is phosphorylated at the number 1 and 3 carbons.
[src:acetyl-coa/1-3-bisphosphoglycerate] The result of this phosphorylation gives 1,3BPG important biological properties such as the ability to donate a phosphate group to adenosine diphosphate (ADP) in order to form the energy storage molecule adenosine triphosphate (ATP).
[src:acetyl-coa/1-3-bisphosphoglycerate] Compound C00118 at KEGG Pathway Database.
[src:acetyl-coa/1-3-bisphosphoglycerate] Enzyme 1.2.1.12 at KEGG Pathway Database.
[src:acetyl-coa/1-3-bisphosphoglycerate] Compound C00236 at KEGG Pathway Database.
[src:acetyl-coa/1-3-bisphosphoglycerate] Enzyme 2.7.2.3 at KEGG Pathway Database.
[src:acetyl-coa/1-3-bisphosphoglycerate] Compound C00197 at KEGG Pathway Database.
[src:acetyl-coa/1-3-bisphosphoglycerate] 1,3BPG is a macroergic metabolic intermediate in the glycolytic pathway.
[src:acetyl-coa/1-3-bisphosphoglycerate] It is created by the exergonic oxidation of the aldehyde in glyceraldehyde 3-phosphate.
[src:acetyl-coa/1-3-bisphosphoglycerate] The result of this oxidation is the conversion of the aldehyde group into a carboxylic acid group which drives the formation of an acyl phosphate bond.
[src:acetyl-coa/1-3-bisphosphoglycerate] The latter reaction is the only step in the glycolytic pathway in which NAD+ is converted into NADH.
[src:acetyl-coa/1-3-bisphosphoglycerate] The formation reaction of 1,3BPG requires the presence of an enzyme called glyceraldehyde-3-phosphate dehydrogenase.
[src:acetyl-coa/1-3-bisphosphoglycerate] The high-energy acyl phosphate bond of 1,3BPG is important in respiration as it assists in the formation of ATP.
[src:acetyl-coa/1-3-bisphosphoglycerate] The molecule of ATP created during the following reaction is the first molecule produced during respiration.
[src:acetyl-coa/1-3-bisphosphoglycerate] The transfer of an inorganic phosphate from the carboxyl group on 1,3BPG to ADP to form ATP is reversible due to a low ΔG.
[src:acetyl-coa/1-3-bisphosphoglycerate] This is as a result of one acyl phosphate bond being cleaved whilst another is created.
[src:acetyl-coa/1-3-bisphosphoglycerate] This reaction is not naturally spontaneous and requires the presence of a catalyst.
[src:acetyl-coa/1-3-bisphosphoglycerate] This role is performed by the enzyme phosphoglycerate kinase.
[src:acetyl-coa/1-3-bisphosphoglycerate] During the reaction phosphoglycerate kinase undergoes a substrate induced conformational change similar to another metabolic enzyme called hexokinase.
[src:acetyl-coa/1-3-bisphosphoglycerate] Because two molecules of glyceraldehyde-3-phosphate are formed during glycolysis from one molecule of glucose, 1,3BPG can be said to be responsible for two of the ten molecules of ATP produced during the entire process.
[src:acetyl-coa/1-3-bisphosphoglycerate] Glycolysis also uses two molecules of ATP in its initial stages as a committed and irreversible step.
[src:acetyl-coa/1-3-bisphosphoglycerate] For this reason glycolysis is not reversible and has a net produce of 2 molecules of ATP and two of NADH.
[src:acetyl-coa/1-3-bisphosphoglycerate] The two molecules of NADH themselves go on to produce approximately 3 molecules of ATP each.
[src:acetyl-coa/1-3-bisphosphoglycerate] 1,3-BPG has a very similar role in the Calvin cycle to its role in the glycolytic pathway.
[src:acetyl-coa/1-3-bisphosphoglycerate] For this reason both reactions are said to be analogous.
[src:acetyl-coa/1-3-bisphosphoglycerate] However the reaction pathway is effectively reversed.
[src:acetyl-coa/1-3-bisphosphoglycerate] The only other major difference between the two reactions is that NADPH is used as an electron donor in the calvin cycle whilst NAD+ is used as an electron acceptor in glycolysis.
[src:acetyl-coa/1-3-bisphosphoglycerate] In this reaction cycle 1,3BPG originates from 3-phosphoglycerate and is made into glyceraldehyde 3-phosphate by the action of specific enzymes.
[src:acetyl-coa/1-3-bisphosphoglycerate] Contrary to the similar reactions of the glycolytic pathway, 1,3BPG in the Calvin cycle does not produce ATP but instead uses it.
[src:acetyl-coa/1-3-bisphosphoglycerate] For this reason it can be considered to be an irreversible and committed step in the cycle.
[src:acetyl-coa/1-3-bisphosphoglycerate] The outcome of this section of the cycle is an inorganic phosphate is removed from 1,3BPG as a hydrogen ion and two electrons are added to the compound+.
[src:acetyl-coa/1-3-bisphosphoglycerate] In complete reverse of the glycolytic pathway reaction, the enzyme phosphoglycerate kinase catalyses the reduction of the carboxyl group of 1,3BPG to form an aldehyde instead.
[src:acetyl-coa/1-3-bisphosphoglycerate] This reaction also releases an inorganic phosphate molecule which is subsequently used as energy for the donation of electrons from the conversion of NADPH to NADP+.
[src:acetyl-coa/1-3-bisphosphoglycerate] Overseeing this latter stage of the reaction is the enzyme glyceraldehyde-phosphate dehydrogenase.
[src:acetyl-coa/1-3-bisphosphoglycerate] During normal metabolism in human erythrocytes, ≈19% of the 1,3BPG produced does not go any further in the glycolytic pathway.
[src:acetyl-coa/1-3-bisphosphoglycerate] It is instead shunted through the Luebering–Rapoport pathway involving the reduction of ATP in the red blood cells.
[src:acetyl-coa/1-3-bisphosphoglycerate] During this alternate pathway it is made into a similar molecule called 2,3-bisphosphoglyceric acid (2,3BPG).
[src:acetyl-coa/1-3-bisphosphoglycerate] 2,3BPG is used as a mechanism to oversee the efficient release of oxygen from hemoglobin.
[src:acetyl-coa/1-3-bisphosphoglycerate] Levels of this 1,3BPG will raise in a patient's blood when oxygen levels are low as this is one of the mechanisms of acclimatization.
[src:acetyl-coa/1-3-bisphosphoglycerate] Low oxygen levels trigger a rise in 1,3BPG levels which in turn raises the level of 2,3BPG which alters the efficiency of oxygen dissociation from hemoglobin.
[src:acetyl-coa/1-deoxy-d-xylulose-5-phosphate] The enzyme involved in making 1-deoxy-d-xylulose 5-phosphate (DXP) is DXP synthase.
[src:acetyl-coa/1-deoxy-d-xylulose-5-phosphate] The mechanism follows a catalysis of decarboxylative condensation of pyruvate and d-glyceraldehyde 3-phosphate to produce DXP.
[src:acetyl-coa/1-deoxy-d-xylulose-5-phosphate] In addition, the molecule is involved in making thiamine (vitamin B1) and pyridoxol (vitamin B6).
[src:acetyl-coa/1-deoxy-d-xylulose-5-phosphate] The non-mevalonate pathway intermediate 1-deoxy-d-xylulose 5-phosphate (DXP) also acts as a precursor in making isoprenoids in many species such as bacteria, plants, and apicomplexan parasites, contributing to biological diversity.
[src:acetyl-coa/1-pyrroline-5-carboxylic-acid] The stereoisomer (*S*)-1-pyrroline-5-carboxylate (also referred to as L-P5C) is an intermediate metabolite in the biosynthesis and degradation of proline and arginine.
[src:acetyl-coa/1-pyrroline-5-carboxylic-acid] In prokaryotic proline biosynthesis, GSA is synthesized from γ-glutamyl phosphate by the enzyme γ-glutamyl phosphate reductase.
[src:acetyl-coa/1-pyrroline-5-carboxylic-acid] In most eukaryotes, GSA is synthesised from the amino acid glutamate by the bifunctional enzyme 1-pyrroline-5-carboxylate synthase (P5CS).
[src:acetyl-coa/1-pyrroline-5-carboxylic-acid] The human P5CS is encoded by the *ALDH18A1* gene.
[src:acetyl-coa/1-pyrroline-5-carboxylic-acid] The enzyme pyrroline-5-carboxylate reductase converts L-P5C into proline.
[src:acetyl-coa/1-pyrroline-5-carboxylic-acid] In proline degradation, the enzyme proline dehydrogenase produces P5C from proline, and the enzyme 1-pyrroline-5-carboxylate dehydrogenase converts GSA to glutamate.
[src:acetyl-coa/1-pyrroline-5-carboxylic-acid] In many prokaryotes, proline dehydrogenase and P5C dehydrogenase form a bifunctional enzyme that prevents the release of P5C during proline degradation.
[src:acetyl-coa/1-pyrroline-5-carboxylic-acid] A reciprocal regulation of delta 1-pyrroline-5-carboxylate synthetase (P5CS) and proline dehydrogenase genes controls proline levels during and after osmotic stress in plants proportional to the level of proline.
[src:acetyl-coa/1-pyrroline-5-carboxylic-acid] This allows an optimum level of proline to be produced from reduced nitrogen to control osmotic stress.
[src:acetyl-coa/18-methoxycoronaridine] 18-MC was originally developed by Savant HWP and later acquired by MindMed in 2019 for development as a treatment for opioid use disorder.
[src:acetyl-coa/18-methoxycoronaridine] A Phase 1 trial in healthy volunteers was completed in 2022 with favorable safety and tolerability.
[src:acetyl-coa/18-methoxycoronaridine] Due to strategic reprioritization, MindMed discontinued active development of MM-110 in 2023 and has been seeking non-dilutive funding or partners to potentially restart the program; as of 2025 the program remains shelved.
[src:acetyl-coa/18-methoxycoronaridine] A separate Phase 2 trial in Brazil for cutaneous leishmaniasis (initiated 2017) has unknown status with no published results.
[src:acetyl-coa/18-methoxycoronaridine] The sites of action in the brain include the medial habenula, interpeduncular nucleus, dorsolateral tegmentum and basolateral amygdala.
[src:acetyl-coa/18-methoxycoronaridine] (±)-18-MC competitively inhibits α9α10 nAChRs with potencies higher than that at α3β4 and α4β2 nAChRs and directly blocks CaV2.2.
[src:acetyl-coa/18-methoxycoronaridine] A number of derivatives of 18-MC have been developed, with several of them being superior to 18-MC itself, the methoxyethyl congener ME-18-MC being more potent than 18-MC with similar efficacy, and the methylamino analogue 18-MAC being more effective than 18-MC with around the same potency.
[src:acetyl-coa/18-methoxycoronaridine] These compounds were also found to act as selective α3β4 nicotinic acetylcholine antagonists, with little or no effect on NMDA receptors.
[src:acetyl-coa/2-3-oxidosqualene] The stereoisomer (*R*)-2,3-oxidosqualene is an inhibitor of lanosterol synthase.
[src:acetyl-coa/2-amino-3-carboxymuconic-semialdehyde] The enzyme 3-hydroxyanthranilate 3,4-dioxygenase uses oxygen to cleave the aromatic ring of 3-hydroxyanthranilic acid, giving 2-amino-3-carboxymuconic semialdehyde.
[src:acetyl-coa/2-amino-3-carboxymuconic-semialdehyde] The kynurenine pathway of tryptophan catabolism leads to nicotinamide adenine dinucleotide and supplies the nicotinic acid component of that cofactor.
[src:acetyl-coa/2-amino-3-carboxymuconic-semialdehyde] Alternatively, 2-amino-3-carboxymuconic semialdehyde can be acted on by the enzyme aminocarboxymuconate-semialdehyde decarboxylase to give 2-aminomuconic semialdehyde, an unstable open-chain precursor of picolinic acid.
[src:acetyl-coa/acetyl-coa] Coenzyme A (CoASH or CoA) consists of a β-mercaptoethylamine group linked to pantothenic acid (vitamin B5) through an amide linkage and 3'-phosphorylated ADP.
[src:acetyl-coa/acetyl-coa] The acetyl group (indicated in blue in the structural diagram on the right) of acetyl-CoA is linked to the sulfhydryl substituent of the β-mercaptoethylamine group.
[src:acetyl-coa/acetyl-coa] This thioester linkage is a "high energy" bond, which is particularly reactive.
[src:acetyl-coa/acetyl-coa] Hydrolysis of the thioester bond is exergonic (−31.5 kJ/mol).
[src:acetyl-coa/acetyl-coa] CoA is acetylated to acetyl-CoA by the breakdown of carbohydrates through glycolysis and by the breakdown of fatty acids through β-oxidation.
[src:acetyl-coa/acetyl-coa] Acetyl-CoA then enters the citric acid cycle, where the acetyl group is oxidized to carbon dioxide and water, and the energy released is captured in the form of 11 ATP and one GTP per acetyl group.
[src:acetyl-coa/acetyl-coa] Konrad Bloch and Feodor Lynen were awarded the 1964 Nobel Prize in Physiology or Medicine for their discoveries linking acetyl-CoA and fatty acid metabolism.
[src:acetyl-coa/acetyl-coa] Fritz Lipmann won the Nobel Prize in 1953 for his discovery of the cofactor coenzyme A.
[src:acetyl-coa/acetyl-coa] Acetyl-CoA is a metabolic intermediate that is involved in many metabolic pathways in an organism.
[src:acetyl-coa/acetyl-coa] It is produced during the breakdown of glucose, fatty acids, and amino acids, and is used in the synthesis of many other biomolecules, including cholesterol, fatty acids, and ketone bodies.
[src:acetyl-coa/acetyl-coa] Acetyl-CoA is also a key molecule in the citric acid cycle, which is a series of chemical reactions that occur in the mitochondria of cells and is responsible for generating energy in the form of ATP.
[src:acetyl-coa/acetyl-coa] In addition, acetyl-CoA is a precursor for the biosynthesis of various acetyl-chemicals, acting as an intermediate to transfer an acetyl group during the biosynthesis of those acetyl-chemicals.
[src:acetyl-coa/acetyl-coa] Acetyl-CoA is also involved in the regulation of various cellular mechanisms by providing acetyl groups to target amino acid residues for post-translational acetylation reactions of proteins.
[src:acetyl-coa/acetyl-coa] The acetylation of CoA is determined by the carbon sources.
[src:acetyl-coa/acetyl-coa] At high glucose levels, glycolysis takes place rapidly, thus increasing the amount of citrate produced from the citric acid cycle.
[src:acetyl-coa/acetyl-coa] This citrate is then exported to other organelles outside the mitochondria to be broken into acetyl-CoA and oxaloacetate by the enzyme ATP citrate lyase (ACL).
[src:acetyl-coa/acetyl-coa] This principal reaction is coupled with the hydrolysis of ATP.
[src:acetyl-coa/acetyl-coa] At low glucose levels CoA is acetylated using acetate by acetyl-CoA synthetase (ACS), also coupled with ATP hydrolysis.
[src:acetyl-coa/acetyl-coa] Ethanol also serves as a carbon source for acetylation of CoA utilizing the enzyme alcohol dehydrogenase.
[src:acetyl-coa/acetyl-coa] Degradation of branched-chain ketogenic amino acids such as valine, leucine, and isoleucine occurs.
[src:acetyl-coa/acetyl-coa] These amino acids are converted to α-ketoacids by transamination and eventually to isovaleryl-CoA through oxidative decarboxylation by an α-ketoacid dehydrogenase complex.
[src:acetyl-coa/acetyl-coa] Isovaleryl-CoA undergoes dehydrogenation, carboxylation and hydration to form another CoA-derivative intermediate before it is cleaved into acetyl-CoA and acetoacetate.
[src:acetyl-coa/acetyl-coa] Additionally, malonyl-CoA decarboxylase (MCD), present in the cytosol, contributes to the extramitochondrial acetyl-CoA pool by converting malonyl-CoA into acetyl-CoA.
[src:acetyl-coa/acetyl-coa] At high glucose levels, acetyl-CoA is produced through glycolysis.
[src:acetyl-coa/acetyl-coa] Pyruvate undergoes oxidative decarboxylation in which it loses its carboxyl group (as carbon dioxide) to form acetyl-CoA, giving off 33.5 kJ/mol of energy.
[src:acetyl-coa/acetyl-coa] The oxidative conversion of pyruvate into acetyl-CoA is referred to as the **pyruvate dehydrogenase reaction**.
[src:acetyl-coa/acetyl-coa] It is catalyzed by the pyruvate dehydrogenase complex.
[src:acetyl-coa/acetyl-coa] Other conversions between pyruvate and acetyl-CoA are possible.
[src:acetyl-coa/acetyl-coa] For example, pyruvate formate lyase disproportionates pyruvate into acetyl-CoA and formic acid.
[src:acetyl-coa/acetyl-coa] At low glucose levels, the production of acetyl-CoA is linked to β-oxidation of fatty acids.
[src:acetyl-coa/acetyl-coa] Fatty acids are first converted to acyl-CoA.
[src:acetyl-coa/acetyl-coa] Acyl-CoA is then degraded in a four-step cycle of oxidation, hydration, oxidation and thiolysis catalyzed by four respective enzymes, namely acyl-CoA dehydrogenase, enoyl-CoA hydratase, 3-hydroxyacyl-CoA dehydrogenase, and thiolase.
[src:acetyl-coa/acetyl-coa] The cycle produces a new fatty acid chain with two fewer carbons and acetyl-CoA as a byproduct.
[src:acetyl-coa/acetyl-coa] Within mitochondria, MCD similarly facilitates acetyl-CoA production by decarboxylating malonyl-CoA, thereby supporting metabolic flexibility during low-glucose states.
[src:acetyl-coa/e-4-hydroxy-3-methyl-but-2-enyl-pyrophosphate] HMB-PP is an intermediate in the non-mevalonate pathway for the biosynthesis of the isoprenoid precursors isopentenyl pyrophosphate and dimethylallyl pyrophosphate.
[src:acetyl-coa/e-4-hydroxy-3-methyl-but-2-enyl-pyrophosphate] Most gram-negative bacteria, the photosynthetic cyanobacteria and green algae use only this pathway, while higher plants also use the mevalonate pathway.
[src:acetyl-coa/e-4-hydroxy-3-methyl-but-2-enyl-pyrophosphate] The final step in the non-mevalonate pathway is carried out by the enzyme 4-hydroxy-3-methylbut-2-enyl diphosphate reductase, which gives a mixture of dimethylallyl pyrophosphate and isopentenyl pyrophosphate in the ratio of five to one.
[src:acetyl-coa/e-4-hydroxy-3-methyl-but-2-enyl-pyrophosphate] The products are then used in terpenoid biosynthesis.
[src:acetyl-coa/e-4-hydroxy-3-methyl-but-2-enyl-pyrophosphate] HMB-PP is an essential metabolite in most pathogenic bacteria including *Mycobacterium tuberculosis* as well as in malaria parasites, but is absent from the human host.
[src:acetyl-coa/e-4-hydroxy-3-methyl-but-2-enyl-pyrophosphate] HMB-PP is the physiological activator ("phosphoantigen") for human Vγ9/Vδ2 T cells, the major γδ T cell population in peripheral blood.
[src:acetyl-coa/e-4-hydroxy-3-methyl-but-2-enyl-pyrophosphate] With a bioactivity of 0.1 nM it is 10,000-10,000,000 times more potent than any other natural compound, such as IPP or alkyl amines.
[src:acetyl-coa/e-4-hydroxy-3-methyl-but-2-enyl-pyrophosphate] HMB-PP functions in this capacity by binding the B30.2 domain of BTN3A1.
